<h1><span class="latex">L<sup>a</sup>T<sub>e</sub>X</span> Styles</h1>


<p>
OALI books will be typeset in <span class="latex">L<sup>a</sup>T<sub>e</sub>X</span>. Authors can help the project to keep the costs low by
submitting their books (not necessarily the initial manuscript) in <span class="latex">L<sup>a</sup>T<sub>e</sub>X</span> and by sticking to
the styles provided by us.
</p>
<p>
An initial draft of <a href="https://github.com/langsci/latex/blob/master/Guidelines/lsp-guidelines.pdf?raw=true">authors' guidelines and a <span class="latex">L<sup>a</sup>T<sub>e</sub>X</span> tutorial</a> is already available.
</p>
<p>
We will use <a href="http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/XeTeX"><span class="latex">X<sub><span class=revcap>e</span></sub>L<sup>a</sup>T<sub>e</sub>X</span></a> with the following packages:
<ul>
<li>tikz-qtree
<li>adapted version of gb4e for glossed example sentence
<li>references in BibTeX format
</ul>
The <a href="https://github.com/langsci/latex/"><code>langsci</code> class and further stylefiles</a> are available at GitHUB.
</p>
<p>
For XML conversion and the production of e-books it is important to standardize the
packages. Authors who need special packages should inform the coordinators of the project early
on. We will then try to take care of the <span class="latex">L<sup>a</sup>T<sub>e</sub>X</span> to XML conversion. If you want to help with this, you
may <a href="sign/">sign as a developer</a>.
</p>

